le=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px =
0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>When you put these two cognitive mechanisms toge=
ther, you can create an illusion of decline. Thanks to biased exposure, thi=
ngs look bad every day. But thanks to biased memory, when you think back to=
 yesterday, you don&#8217;t remember things being so bad. When you&#8217;re=
 standing in a wasteland but remember a wonderland, the only reasonable con=
clusion is that things have gotten worse.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"=
color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Ev=
er wonder why politicians promise to restore some previous period of glory?=
 It&#8217;s a tactic as old as politics, and it&#8217;s still effective. Tr=
ump promised to &#8220;Make America Great Again.&#8221; Then Biden came in =
and proclaimed that &#8220;America is Back.&#8221; Humans are biased to thi=
nk that things used to be better and that everything is worse today than it=
 was yesterday. And everyone from politicians, to marketers, to your parent=
s known how to play on this bias.</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">But most everyone's thinking=
 is wrong. We are not in the midst of some never ending moral decline. Prog=
ress hasn&#8217;t really stagnated. It is the best time in human history to=
 be born. So why are people so susceptible to this line of pessimistic thin=
king?</p><ol style=3D"margin-top: 0; padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px =
0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: #404040; font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><s=
trong>Biased Exposure: </strong><span>People predominantly encounter and pa=
y attention to negative information about others &#8212; mischief and misde=
eds make the news and dominate our conversations. If it bleeds it reads!</s=
pan></p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: bo=
rder-box; color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; ma=
rgin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong>Biased memory:</strong><span> T=
he negativity of negative information fades faster than the positivity of p=
ositive information. I was a wreck the first time I got dumped, but now I b=
arely remember anything about that relationship. Yet, I could tell you the =
minute details of my first date with my current girlfriend.</span></p></li>=
</ol><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">Taken together, these two biases mean that things look bad e=
veryday, but when you look back you don&#8217;t remember things being so ba=
d.</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;">So why are we sharing this? Well, knowing we have a problem=
 is the first step. We&#8217;re naturally biased towards pessimism. Optimis=
m takes work.</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong><span>(2) </span><a href=3D"https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/22ca5b26-582d-4652-b471-8cc88c9d6e9f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: #404040=
; text-decoration: underline;">Compounding Optimism</a></strong></p><p styl=
e=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;"><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/deb22214-dfab-4996-b79b-e44=
61748808b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U" rel style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">Morgan Housel<=
/a><span> for Collaborative Fund</span></em></p><blockquote style=3D"border=
-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: #=
404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left=
: 20px;"><em>Small ideas mixing and compounding into big ones &#8211; that&=
#8217;s what really drives the world. I think part of the reason pessimism =
is so much easier and more common than optimism is that compound growth is =
not intuitive.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Morgan Housel, in his m=
ost recent essay, explains why optimism takes work. </span><strong>It&#8217=
;s not intuitive</strong><span>. It&#8217;s not intuitive because the under=
lying driver of optimism is compound growth, and compound growth is hard to=
 wrap your head around.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Any story we write about in the=
 Weekly Dose of Optimism is likely the result of hundreds of small ideas, d=
iscoveries, or research papers, compounding on top of each other for hundre=
ds of years. OpenAI doesn&#8217;t happen with out Daniel Faraday demonstrat=
ing the principle of electromagnetic induction in 1831, or the millions of =
other advancements in the subsequent 191 years.</p><p style=3D"color: #4040=
40; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">No matter how =
smart you are, you simply can&#8217;t predict this stuff. So how can you be=
 optimistic about a future that you can&#8217;t predict? It goes back to kn=
owing our limitations. Optimism takes work. It&#8217;s knowing that we can&=
#8217;t predict the future. It&#8217;s knowing that small ideas compound. A=
nd it&#8217;s believing that, if history is any indication, those small ide=
as will compound into progress-driving, world-changing ideas.</p><p style=
=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
"><strong><span>(3) </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/9792e15=
